President Muhammadu Buhari lauded members of the Nigerian Private Sector Coalition Against Covid-19, made of people like Aliko Dangote, Abdulsamad Rabiu of BUA Group, Femi Otedola, Tony Elumelu, Herbert Wigwe, Segun Agbaje and Jim Ovia of UBA, Access, GT, and Zenith Banks, respectively, for contributing N1 billion each to the battle against the Covid-19 pandemic. President Buhari, in a statement yesterday by his spokesperson, Femi Adesina, also hailed them for being in the vanguard of encouraging others in the private sector to do same. The President saluted the public-spiritedness of wealthy Nigerians and organizations for standing up to be counted in the battle against the COVID-19 pandemic. “UBA has equally donated the sum of N5 billion to Nigeria and Africa, former Vice President Atiku Abubakar has pledged N50 million,  while First Bank is partnering with government, the United Nations, and innovative technological firms to provide e-learning solutions to at least one million children under its ‘Keep Them Engaged, Keep Them Safe’ initiative,” the statement added. Coronavirus: UBA to provide N5bn relief support UBA donates N5bn as COVID-19 relief support in Africa Nigeria needs N120bn to combat COVID-19 – Emefiele